# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1984-european-parliament-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-france] European Parliament elections were held in France for the first time on 10 June 1979.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-france] Four parties won seats: the centre right Union for French Democracy the Gaullist Rally for the Republic, the Socialist Party and the French Communist Party.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The **1979 European Parliament election in Ireland** was the Irish component of the 1979 European Parliament election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] These were the first direct elections to the European Parliament, and the first election to be held simultaneously across the entire Island of Ireland since the 1921 Irish elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The election was conducted under the single transferable vote.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] Provisional Sinn Féin did not to contest the election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] However, the relative success of Bernadette McAliskey in Northern Ireland helped prompt Sinn Féin to stand in subsequent European elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The **1979 European Parliament election in Italy** was held on 10 June 1979.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the 1979 Italian general election was held on 3 June, just a week before, the lack of matching between the two elections caused much controversy for wasting public money.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The pure party-list proportional representation was the traditional electoral system of the Italian Republic since its foundation in 1946, so it was naturally adopted to elect the Italian representatives to the European Parliament.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Two levels were used: a national level to divide seats between parties, and a constituency level to distribute them between candidates.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Italian regions were united in 5 constituencies, each electing a group of deputies.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] At national level, seats were divided between party lists using the largest remainder method with Hare quota.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] All seats gained by each party were automatically distributed to their local open lists and their most voted candidates.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Seats are allocated to party lists on a national basis using an electoral quota, with the residue given to the lists with the largest excess over whole quotas.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] An electoral quota is then calculated for each list and used to allocate seats to each list in each of the five electoral regions.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the election took place just a week after the general election, it gave a similar result; however, the minor importance of the European ballot caused a lower turnout, which particularly punished the two major parties, Christian Democracy (DC) and the Italian Communist Party (PCI).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The small Italian Liberal Party (PLI) had a breath of fresh air from this vote, doubling its percentage compared to seven days before.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] An election for Members of the European Parliament representing Netherlands constituency for the 1979–1984 term of the European Parliament was held on 7 June 1979.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] It was part of the wider 1979 European election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] The ten seats were elected using proportional representation, with seats allocated using the D'Hondt method.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] The Labour Party and Political Party of Radicals formed an electoral alliance.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Four parties were able to win seats: the conservative liberal VVD, the progressive liberal D66, the Christian-democratic CDA and the social-democratic Labour Party.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Five other nationally represented parties compete but are unable to win seats.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] 58.12% of the Dutch population turned out on election day.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The **1979 European Parliament election**, was the first European election to be held in the United Kingdom after the European Communities (EC) decided to directly elect representatives to the European Parliament.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Elections were also held in eight other EC states.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] European elections were incorporated into UK law by the European Assembly Elections Act 1978.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Out of the 410 members of the European Parliament, 81 were elected from the UK.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The electoral system was First past the post in England, Scotland and Wales (electing 78 MEPs in total) and Single Transferable Vote in Northern Ireland (electing 3 MEPs).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The result was a landslide victory for the Conservative Party, which won 60 of the 78 seats available in England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Their decisive victory in the general election of the previous month and divisions within the Labour party on whether to stay in the EC probably helped the Conservatives to such a comprehensive victory.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] There was a very low turnout in the election compared with other states, the lowest in Europe.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Voter apathy was an explanation, but it is likely the large number of elections in 1979 had a significant negative effect on turnout.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] There were referendums in Scotland and Wales on devolution in March and the general election in May, as well as local elections in England (not including London) and Wales.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] An election of the delegation from West Germany to the first directly elected European Parliament was held in 1979.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] The CDU/CSU won a plurality of the German seats in the European Parliament, which they retained in every subsequent election as of 2022.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] West Berlin, due to its special status, was ineligible to participate in the election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The **1979 European Parliament election** was a series of parliamentary elections held across all 9 (at the time) European Community member states.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] They were the first European elections to be held, allowing citizens to elect 410 MEPs to the European Parliament, and also the first international election in history.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Seats in the Parliament had been allocated to the states according to population, and in some cases were divided into constituencies, but members sat according to political groups.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Treaty of Rome which established the Communities specified that the European Parliament must be elected by universal suffrage using a common voting system.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Council of the European Union was responsible for setting up the elections but it had procrastinated.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] As a stop-gap measure, members were appointed to the Parliament by the member states from their own national parliaments, as they had done since the Common Assembly.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Parliament was unhappy with this and threatened to take the Council to the European Court of Justice.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Council eventually agreed to elections and the first European Parliament elections were held in 1979 after proposals were put forward in the mid-1970s.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The issue of a common voting method was left undecided, and even to this day the voting methods vary from member state to member state, although all have used some form of proportional representation since 1999.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The former Social Democrat German Chancellor Willy Brandt took an international campaign to France, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands to boost the Socialist group.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] On the other hand, the former Prime Minister of France Jacques Chirac used the election to gauge his popularity against the then-President of France Valéry Giscard d'Estaing, in anticipation of a presidential bid in 1981.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] In June, the 410 members were elected by universal suffrage.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] At the time there were no rules on the system of election to be used.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The electorate took little interest but average voter turnout was 63%.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The lowest turn out was in the United Kingdom with 32.2%: all others were above 50% apart from Denmark.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Aside from Belgium and Luxembourg, where voting is compulsory, the highest turnout was in Italy with 84.9%.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Socialist parties working together under the Europe-wide Confederation of Socialist Parties won the most seats: the resultant Socialist group had 113 MEPs.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Christian Democrat parties united within the pan-European European People's Party came second, with the resultant group having 107 MEPs.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The largest third force was the Conservative European Democrats with 64, followed by Communists with 44.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats had 40 seats, although their candidate was elected as President.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The groups formed were loose coalitions based on the groups founded in previous years, but they soon became the basis for modern European political parties.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Louise Weiss, who was born in 1893 and thus 86 at the time, was found to be Parliament's oldest member and hence presided over the chamber while the election of the President took place (July 1979).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Before that could happen however, she immediately had to deal with Ian Paisley MEP who, in the first speech of the session, protested that the British flag outside the building was flying upside down.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] She dealt with the interruption swiftly.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The confrontation was seen as one of her finest hours and she later confided that, as a grandmother, she was used to dealing with "recalcitrant youngsters".
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] There were five candidates for President of the European Parliament: Giorgio Amendola, Italian Communist; Emma Bonino, Italian Technical Independent; Christian de La Malène, French Progressive Democrat; Simone Veil, French Liberal, and Mario Zagari, Italian Socialist.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] In the first ballot, Veil secured 183 of the 380 votes cast – eight short of the absolute majority needed.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The next closest contender was Zagari with 118 votes, then Amendola with 44, de la Malène with 26 and Bonino with 9.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Bonino and de la Malène dropped out and Veil secured an absolute majority in the second ballot with 192 of the 377 votes cast (Zagari gained 128 and Amendola 47).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Veil was elected as the first President of the elected Parliament, and first female President of the Parliament since it was founded in 1952.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The following were elected as Vice-Presidents: Danielle De March, Basil de Ferranti, Bruno Friedrich, Guido Gonella, Gérard Jacquet, Hans Katzer, Poul Møller, Pierre Pflimlin, Bríd Rodgers, Marcel Albert Vandewiele, Anne Vondeling and Mario Zagari.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Previously the Parliament was a weak consultative assembly, the members of which were part-time.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] With the elections the new body of MEPs were full-time, energetic and more diverse.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] As soon as the Parliament was established the "old guard" MEPs of the larger parties sought to raise the bar at which a European Parliament political group could be formed (the status gave financial support and representation in committees).
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] This move was quickly blocked by smaller groups working together and filibustering the proposal.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The ties formed at this time laid the foundations of the Rainbow group: an alliance of left-wing and green parties which later became the European Greens–European Free Alliance group.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The **1984 European Parliament election** was the first since the inaugural election of 1979 and the 1981 enlargement of the European Community to include Greece.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] It was also the last before the accession of Spain and Portugal in 1986.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] Results showed centre-left and right-wing MEPs profiting at the expense of the far-left and centre-right.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The Socialists consolidated their position as the biggest group in the Parliament, and there were notable changes for the smaller groups, with far-right MEPs forming a group and the coalescence of the Green and Regionalist group known as "Rainbow".
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] There was no single uniform voting system for all member states; each of them adopted its own method, established by national law.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The United Kingdom used a one-round (first-past-the-post) system of 78 constituencies in England, Wales and Scotland, while in Northern Ireland 3 proportional seats were allocated.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] Belgium, Ireland and Italy used a proportional system with subdivision of the territory into constituencies.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The number of seats was the same as before for each member state that took part in the 1979 election.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] Greece, which had joined in 1981, was allocated 24 new seats.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] This raised the number of seats to 434 from 410.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The Socialists increased their share by six seats to 130 seats, up from 124 before the elections.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The Democratic Alliance (formerly Progressive Democrats) also made gains, up by seven to 29 seats.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The People's Party's, the European Democrats, Communists and Liberals all lost seats.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The French National Front and the Italian Social Movement founded a group called the "European Right": the first far-right group in the Parliament.
[src:1984-european-parliament-election/1984-european-parliament-election] The *Technical Group of Independents* was replaced by the *Rainbow Group*, a mixture of Greens and Regionalists.
